.TH "kbuffer_curr_index" 9 "kbuffer_curr_index" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
kbuffer_curr_index \- Return the index of the record
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" kbuffer_curr_index
.BI "(struct kbuffer *kbuf "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "kbuf" 12
The kbuffer to read from
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Returns the index from the start of the data part of
the subbuffer to the current location. Note this is not
from the start of the subbuffer. An index of zero will
point to the first record. Use \fBkbuffer_curr_offset\fP for
the actually offset (that can be used by \fBkbuffer_read_at_offset\fP)
